			    STPJS 260</div>
  <div class="topic">Baptism for the Dead</div>
  <p class="std">A few very important things have been manifested to me in my absence respecting the doctrine
  of baptism for the dead, which I shall communicate to the Saints next Sabbath, if nothing should
  occur to prevent me.</p>
  <p class="wideEllipse">* * *</p>

  <p class="std">President Smith said, &ldquo;I have one remark to make respecting the baptism for the dead<span class="footRef">1</span> to suffice
  for the time being, until I have opportunity to discuss the subject at greater length&mdash;all persons
  baptized for the dead must have a recorder present,<span class="footRef">2</span> that he may be an eyewitness to record<span class="footRef">3</span> and
  testify of the truth<span class="footRef">4</span> and validity of his record. It will be necessary, in the Grand Council, that these
  things be testified to by competent witnesses. Therefore let the recording and witnessing of baptisms
  for the dead be carefully attended to from this time forth. If there is any lack, it may be at the
  expense of our friends; they may not come forth.&rdquo;<span class="footRef">5</span> (Aug. 31, 1842.) DHC 5:139–141.</p>
  <div class="topic">Persecution the Heritage of the Righteous</div>
  <div class="topic centerEmphasis">From an Editorial in the &ldquo;Times and Seasons,&rdquo; by the Prophet</div>
  <hr class="centerQuarter" />
  <p class="wideEllipse">* * *</p>

  <p class="std">Abel was slain for his righteousness,<span class="footRef">6</span> and how many more up to the flood is not of much
  consequence to us now. But if we believe in present revelation, as published in the &ldquo;Times and
  Seasons&rdquo; last spring, Abraham, the prophet of the Lord, was laid upon the iron bedstead for
  slaughter;<span class="footRef">7</span> and the book of Jasher,<span class="footRef">8</span> which has not been disproved as a bad author, says he was cast
  into the fire of the Chaldees. Moses, the man of God,<span class="footRef">9</span> who killed an Egyptian persecutor of the
  children of Israel, was driven from his country and kindred.<span class="footRef">10</span> Elijah had to flee his country, for they
  sought his life,<span class="footRef">11</span>&mdash;and he was fed by ravens.<span class="footRef">12</span> Daniel was cast into a den of lions:<span class="footRef">13</span> Micaiah was fed
  on the bread of affliction;<span class="footRef">14</span> and Jeremiah was cast into the filthy hole under the Temple;<span class="footRef">15</span> and did
  these afflictions come upon these prophets of the Lord on account of transgression? No!  It was the
  iron hand of persecution<span class="footRef">16</span>&mdash;like the chains of Missouri!  And mark&mdash;when these old prophets
  suffered, the vengeance of God, in due time,<span class="footRef">17</span> followed and left the wicked opposers of the Lord&rsquo;s
  anointed<span class="footRef">18</span> like Sodom and Gomorrah;<span class="footRef">19</span> like the Egyptians;<span class="footRef">20</span></p>
